snippet.textDisplay:
On January 17, WHO published a protocol from German researchers with the instructions necessary for any country to manufacture COVID-19 tests. That same day the CDC said it had developed it's own test.

On Feb 5 CDC began testing. The next day WHO said it had already shipped 250,000 test kits. A few days later labs were reporting CDC test where not working as expected. On March 1 launched an investigation into manufacturing defects in CDC test.

Finally on March 9 all states and DC were able to test for COVID-19. The US could have used the German protocol and had a test over one month earlier.
snippet.textOriginal:
On January 17, WHO published a protocol from German researchers with the instructions necessary for any country to manufacture COVID-19 tests. That same day the CDC said it had developed it's own test.

On Feb 5 CDC began testing. The next day WHO said it had already shipped 250,000 test kits. A few days later labs were reporting CDC test where not working as expected. On March 1 launched an investigation into manufacturing defects in CDC test. 

Finally on March 9 all states and DC were able to test for COVID-19. The US could have used the German protocol and had a test over one month earlier.

snippet.textDisplay:
The best use of testing is weekly national random testing at the early stages of the pandemic (February) to identify, isolate, and provide resources to the hot spots. This means that the Federal Government should have randomly tested a representative sample of the all residents of the USA. Individual testing of people that feel sick or who just want a test should have been limited to healthcare workers, first responders and high-risk people with immune deficiencies, cancer, asthma, heart conditions, the elderly, etc. Until there is a cure, the test for individuals in the general population is somewhat useless because we all know the treatment - if you feel sick - self quarantine; if you have trouble breathing or have heart problems - go to the hospital. This is the same course of action whether you have COVID-19, a common cold, the flu, or any other contagious virus. The test isn't going to change that. Even if someone takes a test and comes out negative, that person could be infected within 24 hours after taking the test, so by the time they get the results of the test 3 days later, they could be contagious with COVID-19. Most of the spread of the virus has been from contagious people that show no signs of being sick. That is why weekly random sample testing of the entire population was necessary before 1% of the population is infected. Right now, we are fighting the pandemic blindly because we really don't know how many people have COVID-19 or had COVID-19. Statistical random sampling would give us the data we need to answer these questions and better predict the future and allowed us to flatten the curve much more effectively.


Because hundreds of thousands of people were walking around contagious with the virus without knowing it before the shutdown of many cities and communities, the widespread use of masks for everyone, at work, school, church, sporting events, or in public would have dramatically slow the infection rate and flatten the curve. Image if the government issued a $2 dollar mask every week to every resident of the USA (approximately 350 million people) in February at the cost of less than $700 million dollars per week or $2.8 billion per month, it probably would have saved trillions of dollars we now have to spend (of course healthcare workers would need a lot more expensive masks on a daily basis). The use of masks for the general public will not prevent the spread, but it would dramatically slow the spread of the virus.


I’m also wondering if the government had required everyone to wear a mask in public and had adopted a one week on, one week off strategy for six to eight weeks - might be more effective at slowing the spread of the virus and less damaging to the economy compared to the complete shutdown we are currently experiencing in many states and cities. If anyone feels sick after a week off (the incubation period of the virus is approximately 7 days), they would not be permitted to return to work or school. Business and restaurants would not need to lay off workers because of the pent-up demand after a week off would increase their business more than usual. The impact to the economy would probably be less than half of what we are experiencing today, it would be easier to plan for, more predictable, more organized, reduce uncertainty; it would be much better for the psychology of the people, and less costly to the government. Using good data and the use of artificial intelligence (AI) predictive modelling software, we should be able to analyze the effectiveness of this strategy for the next time.
